<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-998-252  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 998 252.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lan Times  Dec 1989 v6 n12 p73(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Infectious diseases: new to the network industry, viruses andworms have caused their share of trouble.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Baker, Virginia E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Problems of network security infractions and infections loom asmajor concerns for network users.andP;  The same ease of resourcesharing that makes networks attractive as management and researchtools also makes them vulnerable to computer virus attack.andP;  Theproblem is compounded by the fact that security is a low priorityduring the development of network operating systems, which arebuilt with the exigencies of sharing and communicating in mind.andO;Each microcomputer added to a network and each user who gainsaccess to a network increases the danger of worm and virusinfection.andP;  These anomalies are introduced into the networkthrough the ubiquitous bulletin board, communication port anddiskette.andP;  Network users today also have ready access to systemlevels as well as applications.andP;  The social and economicimplications of computer crime are enormous, and need to beaddressed systematically.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ManagementSecurityData ManagementComputer VirusesComputer Crimes.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>